Reason: The melting point of phenyl propyl ether can be predicted by considering the following factors: The base structure here is the benzene ring, with the phenyl group typically serving as a reference. Benzene itself has a melting point of 5.5°C. The propyl group (CCC) can be expected to lower the melting point due to its aliphatic nature, reducing intermolecular forces like hydrogen bonding when compared to benzene, as aliphatic hydrocarbons generally have lower melting points than their aromatic counterparts. The effect of the propyl group might lower the melting point by about 10°C. The ether oxygen (O) is a polar group and can participate in dipole-dipole interactions, but its impact on the melting point is less pronounced because it does not engage in hydrogen bonding as a donor (although it can be an acceptor). Nonetheless, ethers tend to have slightly higher melting points than simple alkanes due to these interactions, so we might predict a slight increase of 5°C due to the ether linkage. Combining these effects, we arrive at an estimated melting point for phenyl propyl ether.
